DPP Survey 2022 Data

Beers

2023-05-08

Thank you (And Disclaimers)

Welcome, one and all, to the slightly overdue results of the 2022 DPP Survey! We had over 2,000 responses, and we cannot thank you all enough for your participation and your thoughts. The survey is a critical tool for us to evaluate the health of the subreddit, get user input on all sorts of aspects of the DPP experience, and learn more about the demographics of our community.

First, though, it’s worth noting that while we tried our best to get the largest sample possible, that does not necessarily mean that we got a completely representative sample. Without information on whether users of certain demographics are more likely to respond to the survey, we cannot adequately control for response bias. That’s an unfortunate but unavoidable limitation. It’s also worth pointing out that the question listed above the legend for each of these plots is often a paraphrased version of the actual survey question - some of those questions were long, and it was necessary to shorten them for space reasons. Finally, we want to emphasize that the presentation of these summary statistics and plots is not intended to convey any specific connotations about the opinions of the mods - it is strictly intended to present the data we gathered in an interpretable and sensible way.

Come with us, and we’ll show you the data!

Summary Demographics

First off, let’s look at some basic demographic information about the DPP population.

And, this’ll be familiar to those of you who have seen previous years’ surveys, but it’s still worth taking the time to explain the format for these charts. Each of these is a stacked barplot, with different demographic groups on the x-axis, and another relevant statistic on the Y-axis. This plot, for example, displays the age breakdown for each gender of DPP user. Later plots will have a text description of the y-axis information accompanying the legend on the right, and most will break things down by age and gender, with one column for the total of all users.

Opinion data

Now we’re past the demographic statistics; the following plots examine how DPP users interact with the sub, and how they feel about a few issues that might affect their use of DPP.

First, do our users feel that it’s important for their partner’s gender to match the gender they’re posting as?

Next, how many users are looking for roleplay, conversation, or both?

More of a matter of curiosity to us, but what do our users mean when they talk about a ‘long-term’ interaction?

And finally, how many partners do our users want to juggle at once? No wrong answers, as always.

Next, we have some questions about ghosting, and here we want to emphasize once more that we don’t take any particular stances here; we want the data to speak for itself.

What proportion of our users have ever ghosted a partner, or been ghosted themselves?

Next, how do our users feel about this? How much do they care about not ghosting and not being ghosted? And do they feel that ghosting can ever be justified?

Posting

These next few questions all had to do with the way DPP users post. First, the precondition for everything else - did they post in 2022?

If so, how often?

Did they post for chat?

And/or for roleplay?

Did they get replies?

And how often did things end well, with a sustained interaction?

Which genders did they post as - their own, others, or perhaps both?

Did they post in search of partners of the same gender, another gender, or both?

We all know and/or love novelty tags, but who’s actually using them?

Replying

The next few questions have to do with replying to posts. Once again the biggest question, did our users actually reply to posts in 2022?

Were they replying to posters of the same gender or another gender?

And were they replying to posts seeking conversation or roleplay?

How often did those replies pan out?

And how often did they result in the proverbial happy ending?

And finally, would they reply to a post that used novelty tags?

Mod Action

The next questions have to do with how users interact with the moderation of DPP.

First, did they get a post removed, however it happened?

Was the removal reason useful to them? We’re always seeking to improve them, but they’re not perfect.

Did they engage with the mod team and ask to have their post restored after edits? In a perfect world this would be 100%.

And, well, did it work?

#Contact Methods

The next questions all have to do with methods of correspondence on DPP.

Factors Influencing Interest

These next few questions all have to do with how users evaluate other DPP users, and what factors might affect their decision to reply to a post or answer an inquiry.

First, account age and post history.

Next, accounts being new - note that this doesn’t mean new to DPP, that’s a bit later.

Is u/friendlyfunDPPer a more welcoming name than u/Generic_Llama777?

Ah, here it is. Is an absence of DPP history important to our users?

And, is a totally blank profile an issue?

Finally, is it important for someone to have a bit of smut under their belt? Keep in mind, some folks delete many of their posts, so sometimes it’s hard to tell.

Satisfaction

These next few questions all have to do with users’ general level of satisfaction with DPP.

First, their happiness with their interactions on the sub - covering just about everything.

Then, their happiness with the content they see on the sub.

And the big one, happiness with the rules.

No less important, satisfaction with the events we offer each week.

And the other big one, satisfaction with DPP moderation.

These two don’t have to do with satisfaction, but they do help us make decisions about how to communicate rules changes. Who’s read the main rules linked in the sidebar, and who’s just read the sidebar?

Finally, how happy are our users with the current time limit between posts, and the current three-per-week repost limit?
